                    <h6 class="section-title bg-white text-start text-primary pe-3">Metal Core PCBs</h6>
                    <p>Metal core printed circuit boards (PCBs) are specialized circuit boards designed with a base 
                        layer of metal, often aluminum or copper, as the core material instead of the traditional 
                        fiberglass epoxy. These boards are used in applications that require better heat 
                        dissipation and thermal conductivity than standard PCBs.</p>

                    <p>The metal core serves as a heat sink, helping to dissipate heat generated by components 
                        more effectively. This feature makes metal core PCBs ideal for applications where thermal 
                        management is crucial, such as in LED lighting, power converters, automotive systems, and 
                        high-power electronic devices.</p>

                    <p>The metal core provides a stable base for mounting power components, ensuring better 
                        performance and reliability by keeping temperatures within safe operating limits. 
                        The choice of metal (aluminum or copper) as the core material depends on the specific 
                        application requirements, such as thermal conductivity, mechanical strength, and cost 
                        considerations.</p>

                    <p>Designing and manufacturing metal core PCBs require specialized techniques due to the 
                        different properties of metal compared to traditional PCB materials. 
                        These boards often involve additional steps and considerations in the fabrication process, 
                        impacting both design and production costs.</p>

                    <p>Overall, metal core PCBs offer advantages in thermal management and reliability for 
                        specific applications that demand efficient heat dissipation and thermal performance.</p>
                </div>
